munity.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/56b4756feb3b30c1b570201c0e2216c4a05a6e1a.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/f1036cc8393b3ef40451d45e9091fb9213bf92ce.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/7/754a0317c68293f33bf12e18ebae4de2b08f81b7.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/5954894f377de2935fd0505a2dfa91e1229e52cd.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/0/05bfab6050393e6c96f3a1bf8e5a5fcb099320ba.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/0/0160df6b10af9f47f73802569b3923b422f58dc3.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/ff0fc320b13a75505e6aa3cb9cccd5f49de22167.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/8/8f875f53214515cd7d91639a705e7a3967643aa7.png"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":" are listed with bullet points. At the bottom, there are buttons labeled \u0022Next\u0022 and \u0022Cancel,\u0022 indicating user navigation options. The purpose of this interface is to guide users through creating a lookup feature within a data management system.\n\n\n  \n In the first step of the wizard, select in the Display Field \u2013 the field you want to display in your drop-down menu. The Name field will automatically be populated using the default naming convention ( EntityName_FieldName ), which we strongly recommend you to keep. \n To set up the Lookup for the drop-down menu, you also need to define the ID filter. Here\u2019s what the form may look like: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/9/9bd29e3cb14f426cdf7dc8bef3cb05512058ce3e.png]\nDescription: The image displays a dialog for the \u0022Create Lookup Wizard\u0022 feature in a software application. The fields in the dialog include: \u0022Name\u0022 with the input \u0022Priority_Name_GetId\u0022, \u0022Display Field\u0022 with the label \u0022Name\u0022 and a dropdown selection, \u0022List Filter\u0022 with a blank input field, and \u0022Id Filter\u0022 with the label \u0022GetId\u0022 and a dropdown selection. At the bottom right, there are two buttons: \u0022Next\u0022 and \u0022Cancel.\u0022 The purpose of this interface appears to be to guide users through creating a lookup configuration for data filtering purposes.\n\n\n  \n Notice that the Lookup name has been automatically extended with the filter, resulting in a final name like  Priority_Name_GetId . Again, sticking to this naming convention is highly recommended. \n In the next step, you\u2019ll see a preview of what the wizard will create: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/9/9575f851d185ff3df6ed984426a4fa9a8bdd1db2.png]\nDescription: The image depicts a user interface for a \u0022Create Lookup Wizard.\u0022 The top area includes the title \u0022Create Lookup Wizard\u0022 and a back navigation arrow on the left. Beneath the title, there is explanatory text stating, \u0022This Wizard create lookup with this parameters:\u0022 followed by a list of parameters: \u0022Name: Priority_Name_GetId,\u0022 \u0022Display Field: Name,\u0022 \u0022List Filter: none,\u0022 and \u0022Id Filter: GetId.\u0022 At the bottom of the window, there are two buttons labeled \u0022Start\u0022 and \u0022Cancel.\u0022 The purpose of the interface is to assist users in configuring a lookup with specified parameters.\n\n\n  \n If you need to make any adjustments, you can go back to the previous step by clicking the arrow at the top of the screen. \n Once you\u2019re satisfied, click  Start  to confirm the creation. A confirmation of the creation will appear: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/9/9845fb69368e4bec97302c8c558ee753ea5a3e33.png]\nDescription: Create Lookup Wizard interface displaying a list with two entries under the \u0022Found In\u0022 column: \u0022LookupPriority_Name_GetId\u0022 (marked with an empty circle) and \u0022Priority_Name_GetId\u0022 (marked with a filled circle). The adjacent \u0022Type\u0022 column indicates \u0022Data Structure\u0022 for the first entry and \u0022Data Service Lookup\u0022 for the second. The bottom of the interface contains two buttons: \u0022Show Result\u0022 and \u0022Close.\u0022 The overall purpose of this interface appears to be for configuring or creating a lookup within a data service context.\n\n\n  \n Click  Show Result  to be directed to the Model Browser under the  Find results  tab: \n   \n You can then click on any of the created items, which will bring you to the Model Browser tree where that item is selected (for example, the newly created Lookup): \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/c/ccc85f6e4f8c3d2d6d7d209e4babdc6513538bce.png]\nDescription: The image presents a Model Browser interface for a software application labeled \u0022myapplication.\u0022 The hierarchical structure shows various categories such as \u0022Common,\u0022 \u0022Data,\u0022 \u0022Functions,\u0022 \u0022Lookups,\u0022 \u0022Tree Structures,\u0022 and \u0022User Interface.\u0022 Under \u0022Data,\u0022 there are subcategories for \u0022Constants,\u0022 \u0022Data Structures,\u0022 and \u0022Database Data Types.\u0022 The \u0022Entities\u0022 section is highlighted, indicating a focus on entity definitions. The \u0022Lookups\u0022 category includes a folder named \u0022Priority_Name_GetId,\u0022 along with subfolders for \u0022Organization Management,\u0022 \u0022Resource Management,\u0022 \u0022Root Menu,\u0022 \u0022Security,\u0022 and \u0022Work Queue.\u0022 The apparent purpose is to organize and manage application data and configurations within a development environment.\n\n\n  \n Double-click on your new Lookup to view its details: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-01T23:46:03"},"vector":[-0.0231966